{"title_page": "Robert C. Martin", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Robert C. Martin\n|image         = Robert Cecil Martin.png\n|image_size    =\n|caption       = Martin in March 2015\n|birth_name    = Robert Cecil Martin\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|5 December 1952}}<ref name=rcm-groupon />\n|birth_place   =\n|death_date    =\n|death_place   =\n|death_cause   =\n|resting_place =\n|resting_place_coordinates =\n|residence     =\n|nationality   = American\n|alias         = \"Uncle Bob\" Martin\n|known_for     = [[Agile Manifesto]], [[SOLID|SOLID principles]]\n|education     =\n|alma_mater    =\n|employer      =\n|occupation    = Software engineer, instructor\n|home_town     =\n|title         =\n|salary        =\n|networth      =\n|height        =\n|weight        =\n|term          =\n|predecessor   =\n|successor     =\n|party         =\n|boards        =\n|religion      =\n|spouse        =\n|partner       =\n|children      =\n|parents       =\n|relations     =\n|signature     =\n|website       = http://cleancoder.com/\n|}}\n[[File:Robert C. Martin surrounded by computers.jpg|thumb|Martin 2020]]\n'''Robert Cecil Martin''', popularly known as \"Uncle Bob\",<ref name=\"rcm-informit\" /> is an American [[software engineer]] and instructor. He is best known for being one of the authors of the [[Agile Manifesto]]<ref name=\"rcm-manifesto\" /> and for developing several software design principles. He was also the editor-in-chief of ''[[C++ Report]]'' magazine and served as the first chairman of the Agile Alliance.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Companies==\nMartin operated{{when|date=March 2020}} a now-defunct company, Object Mentor, which provided instructor-led training courses about [[extreme programming]] methodology.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\nMartin currently{{when|date=March 2020}} operates two companies:{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\n*Uncle Bob Consulting, which provides consulting and training services\n*Clean Coders, which provides training videos\n\n== Software principles and advocacy ==\nMost of the principles Martin promotes were invented by him. The [[Liskov substitution principle]] was, however, devised by [[Barbara Liskov]].{{fact|date=March 2020}} Additionally, the [[Open\u2013closed principle]] was conceived by [[Bertrand Meyer]].{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\nFive of the main principles advocated by Martin have become known collectively as the \"[[SOLID|SOLID principles]]\" and have received wide attention in the software industry.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\nMartin has authored numerous books and magazine articles. He is also an outspoken advocate of [[software craftsmanship]], [[agile software development]], and [[Test-driven development|test-driven software development]].{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Publications ==\n* 2002. ''Agile Software Development, Principles, Patterns, and Practices''. Pearson. {{ISBN|978-0135974445}}.\n* 2009. ''Clean Code: A Handbook of Agile Software Craftsmanship''. Prentice Hall. {{ISBN|978-0132350884}}.\n* 2011. ''The Clean Coder: A Code Of Conduct For Professional Programmers''. Prentice Hall. {{ISBN|978-0137081073}}.\n* 2017. ''Clean Architecture: A Craftsman's Guide to Software Structure and Design''. Prentice Hall. {{ISBN|978-0134494166}}.\n* 2019. ''Clean Agile: Back to Basics''. Prentice Hall. {{ISBN|978-0135781869}}.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Agile Manifesto]]\n*[[SOLID|SOLID principles]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist | refs=\n\n<ref name=\"rcm-groupon\">{{cite AV media|author=Groupon OnAir|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3zTtAjkVRDM|title=The Future of Programming with Uncle Bob Martin|publisher=YouTube|date=2016-07-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"rcm-informit\">{{cite book |url=http://www.informit.com/articles/article.aspx?p=1711821 |title=Do Professional Programmers Need a Code of Conduct? An Interview with Robert C. \"Uncle Bob\" Martin |last1=Heusser |first1=Matthew |last2=Martin |first2=Robert C. |date=2011-05-10 |website=[[InformIT (publisher)|InformIT]] |access-date=2015-02-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=rcm-manifesto>{{cite web |url=http://www.agilemanifesto.org/authors.html |title=Authors: The Agile Manifesto |date=2001 |website=Manifesto for Agile Software Development |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Design Patterns patterns}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin, Robert Cecil}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American software engineers]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Agile software development]]\n[[Category:Software design patterns]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Robert C. Martin\n|image         = Robert Cecil Martin.png\n|image_size    =\n|caption       = Martin in March 2015\n|birth_name    = Robert Cecil Martin\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|5 December 1952}}<ref name=rcm-groupon />\n|birth_place   =\n|death_date    =\n|death_place   =\n|death_cause   =\n|resting_place =\n|resting_place_coordinates =\n|residence     =\n|nationality   = American\n|alias         = \"Uncle Bob\" Martin\n|known_for     = [[Agile Manifesto]], [[SOLID|SOLID principles]]\n|education     =\n|alma_mater    =\n|employer      =\n|occupation    = Software engineer, instructor\n|home_town     =\n|title         =\n|salary        =\n|networth      =\n|height        =\n|weight        =\n|term          =\n|predecessor   =\n|successor     =\n|party         =\n|boards        =\n|religion      =\n|spouse        =\n|partner       =\n|children      =\n|parents       =\n|relations     =\n|signature     =\n|website       = http://cleancoder.com/\n|}}\n'''Robert Cecil Martin''', popularly known as \"Uncle Bob\",<ref name=rcm-informit /> is an American [[software engineer]] and instructor. He is best known for being one of the authors of the [[Agile Manifesto]]<ref name=rcm-manifesto /> and for developing several software design principles. He was also the editor-in-chief of ''[[C++ Report]]'' magazine and served as the first chairman of the Agile Alliance.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Companies==\nMartin operated{{when|date=March 2020}} a now-defunct company, Object Mentor, which provided instructor-led training courses about [[extreme programming]] methodology.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\nMartin currently{{when|date=March 2020}} operates two companies:{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\n*Uncle Bob Consulting, which provides consulting and training services\n*Clean Coders, which provides training videos\n\n== Software principles and advocacy ==\nMost of the principles Martin promotes were invented by him. The [[Liskov substitution principle]] was, however, devised by [[Barbara Liskov]].{{fact|date=March 2020}} Additionally, the [[Open\u2013closed principle]] was conceived by [[Bertrand Meyer]].{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\nFive of the main principles advocated by Martin have become known collectively as the \"[[SOLID|SOLID principles]]\" and have received wide attention in the software industry.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\nMartin has authored numerous books and magazine articles. He is also an outspoken advocate of [[software craftsmanship]], [[agile software development]], and [[Test-driven development|test-driven software development]].{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Publications ==\n* 2002. ''Agile Software Development, Principles, Patterns, and Practices''. Pearson. {{ISBN|978-0135974445}}.\n* 2009. ''Clean Code: A Handbook of Agile Software Craftsmanship''. Prentice Hall. {{ISBN|978-0132350884}}.\n* 2011. ''The Clean Coder: A Code Of Conduct For Professional Programmers''. Prentice Hall. {{ISBN|978-0137081073}}.\n* 2017. ''Clean Architecture: A Craftsman's Guide to Software Structure and Design''. Prentice Hall. {{ISBN|978-0134494166}}.\n* 2019. ''Clean Agile: Back to Basics''. Prentice Hall. {{ISBN|978-0135781869}}.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Agile Manifesto]]\n*[[SOLID|SOLID principles]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist | refs=\n\n<ref name=\"rcm-groupon\">{{cite AV media|author=Groupon OnAir|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3zTtAjkVRDM|title=The Future of Programming with Uncle Bob Martin|publisher=YouTube|date=2016-07-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"rcm-informit\">{{cite book |url=http://www.informit.com/articles/article.aspx?p=1711821 |title=Do Professional Programmers Need a Code of Conduct? An Interview with Robert C. \"Uncle Bob\" Martin |last1=Heusser |first1=Matthew |last2=Martin |first2=Robert C. |date=2011-05-10 |website=[[InformIT (publisher)|InformIT]] |access-date=2015-02-26}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=rcm-manifesto>{{cite web |url=http://www.agilemanifesto.org/authors.html |title=Authors: The Agile Manifesto |date=2001 |website=Manifesto for Agile Software Development |access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Design Patterns patterns}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin, Robert Cecil}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American software engineers]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Agile software development]]\n[[Category:Software design patterns]]\n", "name_user": "Angelacleancoder", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added a current picture.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_C._Martin"}
{"title_page": "100 Greatest African Americans", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox book\n| name              = 100 Greatest African Americans: A Biographical Encyclopedia\n| image             = 100 Greatest African Americans.jpg\n| caption           = \n| alt               = \n| author            = [[Molefi Kete Asante]]\n| cover_artist      = \n| country           = United States\n| language          = English\n| subject           = African-American biographies\n| published         = 2002\n| publisher         = [[Prometheus Books]]\n| media_type        = Print\n| pages             = 345\n| awards            = \n| isbn              = 978-1-57392-963-9\n| oclc              = \n| dewey             = \n| congress          = \n}}\n'''''100 Greatest African Americans''''' is a [[biographical dictionary]] of one hundred [[greatness|historically great]] [[African American|Black American]]s (in alphabetical order; that is, they are not ranked), as assessed by [[Temple University]] professor [[Molefi Kete Asante]] in 2002.\n\n==Criteria== Ira Aldridge\nAsante used five factors in establishing the list:\n\n*\"significance in the general progress of African-Americans toward full equality in the American social and political system\"\n*\"self-sacrifice and a willingness to take great risks for the collective good\"\n*\"unusual will and determination in the face of great danger and against the most stubborn odds\"\n*\"a consistent posture toward raising the social, cultural and economic status of African Americans\"\n*\"personal achievement that reveals the best qualities of the African American people\"\n\n''[[Reference and User Services Quarterly]]'' reviewed the list positively in 2003, while noting the subjectivity in judging greatness, particularly for contemporary individuals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hughes|first=M. Elaine|date=Summer 2003|title='100 Greatest African Americans: A Biographical Encyclopedia' Book Review|url=https://scholarworks.gsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1018&context=univ_lib_facpub|journal=Reference and User Services Quarterly|volume=42|issue=4|pages=356|via=}}</ref>\n\n==The list ==\n<!-- This is the list as created by professor Asante in 2002. Please do not add or remove the names in the list. -->                                                     \n#[[Hank Aaron]]\n#[[Chris Rock]]\n#[[Muhammad Ali]]\n#[[Richard Allen (bishop)|Richard Allen]]\n#[[Marian Anderson]]\n#[[Maya Angelou]]\n#[[Arthur Ashe]]\n#[[Crispus Attucks]]\n#[[James Baldwin]]\n#[[Benjamin Banneker]]\n#[[Amiri Baraka]]\n#[[Romare Bearden]]\n#[[Mary McLeod Bethune]]\n#[[Guion Bluford]]\n#[[Arna Bontemps]]\n#[[Edward W. Brooke]]\n#[[Gwendolyn Brooks]]\n#[[Blanche K. Bruce]]\n#[[Ralph Bunche]]\n#[[George Washington Carver]]\n#[[Shirley Chisholm]]\n#[[Kenneth B. Clark]]\n#[[John Henrik Clarke]]\n#[[John Coltrane]]\n#[[Bill Cosby]]\n#[[Alexander Crummell]]\n#[[Countee Cullen]]\n#[[Benjamin O. Davis, Jr.]]\n#[[Martin R. Delany]]\n#[[Frederick Douglass]]\n#[[Charles R. Drew|Charles Drew]]\n#[[W. E. B. Du Bois]]\n#[[Paul Laurence Dunbar]]\n#[[Katherine Dunham]]\n#[[Duke Ellington]]\n#[[James Forten]]\n#[[John Hope Franklin]]\n#[[Henry Highland Garnet]]\n#[[Marcus Garvey]]\n#[[Prince Hall]]\n#[[Fannie Lou Hamer]]\n#[[Lorraine Hansberry]]\n#[[Dorothy Height]]\n#[[Matthew Henson]]\n#[[Charles Hamilton Houston]]\n#[[Langston Hughes]]\n#[[Zora Neale Hurston]]\n#[[Jesse Jackson]]\n#[[Mae Jemison]]\n#[[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]]\n#[[James Weldon Johnson]]\n#[[John H. Johnson]]\n#[[Percy Julian]]\n#[[Ernest Just]]\n#[[Maulana Karenga]]\n#[[Martin Luther King, Jr.]]\n#[[Edmonia Lewis]]\n#[[Alain Locke]]\n#[[Joe Louis]]\n#[[Thurgood Marshall]]\n#[[Benjamin E. Mays]]\n#[[Elijah McCoy]]\n#[[Claude McKay]]\n#[[Oscar Micheaux]]\n#[[Dorie Miller]]\n#[[Garrett Morgan]]\n#[[Toni Morrison]]\n#[[Elijah Muhammad]]\n#[[Jesse Owens]]\n#[[Rosa Parks]]\n#[[Adam Clayton Powell, Jr.]]\n#[[Colin Powell]]\n#[[A. Philip Randolph]]\n#[[Hiram Revels]]\n#[[Paul Robeson]]\n#[[Jackie Robinson]]\n#[[John Russwurm]]\n#[[Arturo Schomburg]]\n#[[Benjamin \"Pop\" Singleton]]\n#[[Mary Church Terrell]]\n#[[William Monroe Trotter]]\n#[[Sojourner Truth]]\n#[[Harriet Tubman]]\n#[[Kwame Ture]]\n#[[Henry McNeal Turner]]\n#[[Nat Turner]]\n#[[David Walker (abolitionist)|David Walker]]\n#[[Madame C. J. Walker]]\n#[[Booker T. Washington]]\n#[[Ida B. Wells-Barnett]]\n#[[Phillis Wheatley]]\n#[[Walter F. White]]\n#[[Roy Wilkins]]\n#[[Daniel Hale Williams]]\n#[[August Wilson]]\n#[[Oprah Winfrey]]\n#[[Tiger Woods]]\n#[[Carter G. Woodson]]\n#[[Richard Wright (author)|Richard Wright]]\n#[[Malcolm X]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Lists of African Americans]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* {{cite book |title=100 Greatest African Americans: A Biographical Encyclopedia |url= http://www.listology.com/tittleiota/list/list-100-greatest-african-americans-molefi-kete-asante-2002 |last=Asante |first=Molefi Kete |year=2002 |publisher=Prometheus |location=Amherst, NY |isbn=978-1-57392-963-9|ref=Asante}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Asante|first1=Molefi Kete|title=100 Greatest African Americans: A Biographical Encyclopedia|date=2002|publisher=Prometheus Books|isbn=9781615924233|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HwuGTSnc2CsC&lpg=PA7&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=18 January 2018|language=en}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Hughes|first1=M. Elaine|title=100 Greatest African Americans: A Biographical Encyclopedia|date=2003|url=https://scholarworks.gsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.com/&httpsredir=1&article=1018&context=univ_lib_facpub|journal=Book Review. Reference and User Services Quarterly|volume=42 |issue=4|pages=356|accessdate=6 February 2018|language=en}}\n\n[[Category:2002 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books about African-American history]]\n[[Category:Lists of African-American people]]\n[[Category:Prometheus Books books]]\n[[Category:Top people lists|African American]]\n[[Category:United States biographical dictionaries|African American]]\n[[Category:21st-century encyclopedias]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox book\n| name              = 100 Greatest African Americans: A Biographical Encyclopedia\n| image             = 100 Greatest African Americans.jpg\n| caption           = \n| alt               = \n| author            = [[Molefi Kete Asante]]\n| cover_artist      = \n| country           = United States\n| language          = English\n| subject           = African-American biographies\n| published         = 2002\n| publisher         = [[Prometheus Books]]\n| media_type        = Print\n| pages             = 345\n| awards            = \n| isbn              = 978-1-57392-963-9\n| oclc              = \n| dewey             = \n| congress          = \n}}\n'''''100 Greatest African Americans''''' is a [[biographical dictionary]] of one hundred [[greatness|historically great]] [[African American|Black American]]s (in alphabetical order; that is, they are not ranked), as assessed by [[Temple University]] professor [[Molefi Kete Asante]] in 2002.\n\n==Criteria==\nAsante used five factors in establishing the list:\n\n*\"significance in the general progress of African-Americans toward full equality in the American social and political system\"\n*\"self-sacrifice and a willingness to take great risks for the collective good\"\n*\"unusual will and determination in the face of great danger and against the most stubborn odds\"\n*\"a consistent posture toward raising the social, cultural and economic status of African Americans\"\n*\"personal achievement that reveals the best qualities of the African American people\"\n\n''[[Reference and User Services Quarterly]]'' reviewed the list positively in 2003, while noting the subjectivity in judging greatness, particularly for contemporary individuals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hughes|first=M. Elaine|date=Summer 2003|title='100 Greatest African Americans: A Biographical Encyclopedia' Book Review|url=https://scholarworks.gsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1018&context=univ_lib_facpub|journal=Reference and User Services Quarterly|volume=42|issue=4|pages=356|via=}}</ref>\n\n==The list ==\n<!-- This is the list as created by professor Asante in 2002. Please do not add or remove the names in the list. -->                                                     \n#[[Hank Aaron]]\n#[[Ira Aldridge]]\n#[[Muhammad Ali]]\n#[[Richard Allen (bishop)|Richard Allen]]\n#[[Marian Anderson]]\n#[[Maya Angelou]]\n#[[Arthur Ashe]]\n#[[Crispus Attucks]]\n#[[James Baldwin]]\n#[[Benjamin Banneker]]\n#[[Amiri Baraka]]\n#[[Romare Bearden]]\n#[[Mary McLeod Bethune]]\n#[[Guion Bluford]]\n#[[Arna Bontemps]]\n#[[Edward W. Brooke]]\n#[[Gwendolyn Brooks]]\n#[[Blanche K. Bruce]]\n#[[Ralph Bunche]]\n#[[George Washington Carver]]\n#[[Shirley Chisholm]]\n#[[Kenneth B. Clark]]\n#[[John Henrik Clarke]]\n#[[John Coltrane]]\n#[[Bill Cosby]]\n#[[Alexander Crummell]]\n#[[Countee Cullen]]\n#[[Benjamin O. Davis, Jr.]]\n#[[Martin R. Delany]]\n#[[Frederick Douglass]]\n#[[Charles R. Drew|Charles Drew]]\n#[[W. E. B. Du Bois]]\n#[[Paul Laurence Dunbar]]\n#[[Katherine Dunham]]\n#[[Duke Ellington]]\n#[[James Forten]]\n#[[John Hope Franklin]]\n#[[Henry Highland Garnet]]\n#[[Marcus Garvey]]\n#[[Prince Hall]]\n#[[Fannie Lou Hamer]]\n#[[Lorraine Hansberry]]\n#[[Dorothy Height]]\n#[[Matthew Henson]]\n#[[Charles Hamilton Houston]]\n#[[Langston Hughes]]\n#[[Zora Neale Hurston]]\n#[[Jesse Jackson]]\n#[[Mae Jemison]]\n#[[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]]\n#[[James Weldon Johnson]]\n#[[John H. Johnson]]\n#[[Percy Julian]]\n#[[Ernest Just]]\n#[[Maulana Karenga]]\n#[[Martin Luther King, Jr.]]\n#[[Edmonia Lewis]]\n#[[Alain Locke]]\n#[[Joe Louis]]\n#[[Thurgood Marshall]]\n#[[Benjamin E. Mays]]\n#[[Elijah McCoy]]\n#[[Claude McKay]]\n#[[Oscar Micheaux]]\n#[[Dorie Miller]]\n#[[Garrett Morgan]]\n#[[Toni Morrison]]\n#[[Elijah Muhammad]]\n#[[Jesse Owens]]\n#[[Rosa Parks]]\n#[[Adam Clayton Powell, Jr.]]\n#[[Colin Powell]]\n#[[A. Philip Ran