ticles.latimes.com/1987-07-05/books/bk-2118_1_french-way online review]\n* Rothermund, Dietmar. ''Memories of Post-Imperial Nations: The Aftermath of Decolonization, 1945\u20132013'' (2015) [https://www.amazon.co.uk/Memories-Post-Imperial-Nations-Aftermath-Decolonization/dp/1107102294/ excerpt]; Compares the impact on Great Britain, the Netherlands, Belgium, France, Portugal, Italy and Japan\n* Singer, Barnett, and John Langdon. ''Cultured Force: Makers and Defenders of the French Colonial Empire'' (2008)\n* Thomas, Martin, ed. ''The French Colonial Mind, Volume 1: Mental Maps of Empire and Colonial Encounters'' (France Overseas: Studies in Empire and D) (2012); ''The French Colonial Mind, Volume 2: Violence, Military Encounters, and Colonialism'' (2012)\n\n===Historiography and memoir===\n* Bennington, Alice. \"Writing Empire? The Reception of Post-Colonial Studies in France.\" ''Historical Journal'' (2016) 59#4: 1157\u20131186. [https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/historical-journal/article/div-classtitlerewriting-empire-the-reception-of-post-colonial-studies-in-francea-hreffns01-ref-typefnadiv/32DA3F5C79BF6B46BE39A67840BF1D36 abstract]\n* Dubois, Laurent. \"The French Atlantic,\" in ''Atlantic History: A Critical Appraisal,'' ed. by Jack P. Greene and Philip D. Morgan, (Oxford UP, 2009) pp 137\u201361\n* Dwyer, Philip. \"Remembering and Forgetting in Contemporary France: Napoleon, Slavery, and the French History Wars,\" ''French Politics, Culture & Society'' (2008) 26#3 pp 110\u2013122.\n* {{cite journal |first=Rupert |last=Emerson |title=Colonialism |journal=Journal of Contemporary History |volume=4 |issue=1 |year=1969 |pages=3\u201316 |doi=10.1177/002200946900400101}}.\n* Greer, Allan. \"National, Transnational, and Hypernational Historiographies: New France Meets Early American History,\" ''Canadian Historical Review,'' (2010) 91#4 pp 695\u2013724, [http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/canadian_historical_review/v091/91.4.greer.html in Project MUSE]\n* Hodson, Christopher, and Brett Rushforth, \"Absolutely Atlantic: Colonialism and the Early Modern French State in Recent Historiography,\" ''History Compass,'' (January 2010) 8#1 pp 101\u2013117\n* Lawrence, Adria K. ''Imperial Rule and the Politics of Nationalism: Anti-Colonial Protest in the French Empire'' (Cambridge UP, 2013) [https://issforum.org/roundtables/7-18-imperial-rule-nationalism online reviews]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.frenchcolonial.org/ French Colonial Historical Society]\n* [http://www.h-france.net/mobile.html H-FRANCE, daily discussions and book reviews]\n* [http://www.frenchcolonial.org/ French Colonial Historical Society]\n* [http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/french_colonial_history/ ''French Colonial History''] an annual volume of refereed, scholarly articles\n\n{{Former French colonies|state=uncollapsed}}\n{{Colonialism}}\n{{New France}}\n{{French Indochina}}\n{{French colonial campaigns}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:French Colonial Empire}}\n[[Category:Former French colonies| ]]\n[[Category:French colonial empire| ]]\n[[Category:History of European colonialism]]\n[[Category:Overseas empires]]\n[[Category:1534 establishments in the French colonial empire]]\n[[Category:1946 disestablishments in the French colonial empire]]\n", "name_user": "Jules Agathias", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_colonial_empire"}
{"title_page": "Joe Flaherty (politician)", "text_new": "{{confuse|Joe Flaherty}}\n{{short description|Irish Fianna F\u00e1il politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Joe Flaherty \n| honorific-suffix = [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]\n| image        = Joe Flaherty (politician).jpeg\n| office       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start   = [[2020 Irish general election|February 2020]]\n| term_end     = \n| constituency = [[Longford\u2013Westmeath (D\u00e1il constituency)|Longford\u2013Westmeath]]\n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   =\n| birth_place  = [[Mullingar]], [[County Westmeath]], Ireland\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party        = [[Fianna F\u00e1il]]\n| spouse       =\n| children     = 3\n| alma_mater   =\n| website      =\n|}}\n'''Joe Flaherty''' is an Irish [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] politician who has been a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) for the [[Longford\u2013Westmeath (D\u00e1il constituency)|Longford\u2013Westmeath]] constituency since the [[2020 Irish general election|2020 general election]].<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Joe-Flaherty.D.2020-02-08/|title=Joe Flaherty|work=Oireachtas Members Database|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Current TDs}}\n{{Fianna F\u00e1il}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flaherty, Joe}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the 33rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Fianna F\u00e1il TDs]]\n\n{{TeachtaD\u00e1la-stub}}\n{{FiannaF\u00e1il-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish Fianna F\u00e1il politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Joe Flaherty \n| honorific-suffix = [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]\n| image        = Joe Flaherty (politician).jpeg\n| office       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start   = [[2020 Irish general election|February 2020]]\n| term_end     = \n| constituency = [[Longford\u2013Westmeath (D\u00e1il constituency)|Longford\u2013Westmeath]]\n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   =\n| birth_place  = [[Mullingar]], [[County Westmeath]], Ireland\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party        = [[Fianna F\u00e1il]]\n| spouse       =\n| children     = 3\n| alma_mater   =\n| website      =\n|}}\n'''Joe Flaherty''' is an Irish [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] politician who has been a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) for the [[Longford\u2013Westmeath (D\u00e1il constituency)|Longford\u2013Westmeath]] constituency since the [[2020 Irish general election|2020 general election]].<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Joe-Flaherty.D.2020-02-08/|title=Joe Flaherty|work=Oireachtas Members Database|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Current TDs}}\n{{Fianna F\u00e1il}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flaherty, Joe}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the 33rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Fianna F\u00e1il TDs]]\n\n{{TeachtaD\u00e1la-stub}}\n{{FiannaF\u00e1il-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "47.30.164.36", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Flaherty_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "McMichael Canadian Art Collection", "text_new": "{{Infobox museum\n|name          = McMichael Canadian Art Collection\n|image         = Gallery New-Entrance Credit-Art2Print-Images (7538295154).jpg\n|caption       = Entrance to McMichael Canadian Art Collection's main building\n|coordinates   = {{coord|43.840776|-79.625205|display=inline,title}}\n|established   = {{start date and age|1965|7|8|df=yes}}{{notetag|The following date is when the institution was first established as a publicly-managed institution. The institution was opened to the public on 8 July 1966, and was formally incorporated into a crown corporation on 30 November 1972. The institution's permanent collection originates from the private collection of Robert and Signe McMichael, which was started in 1955.}}\n|location      = 10365 Islington Avenue,<br>[[Vaughan]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n|type          = [[Art museum]]\n|visitors      = 105,208{{notetag|Total attendance from April 2018 to March 2019.}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mcmichael.com/wp-content/uploads/Annual-Report-2018-19_ENG.pdf|title=Letter from the Executive Director|page=4|work=McMichael Canadian Art Collection 2018\u201319 Annual Report|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|year=2019}}</ref>\n|owner         = [[Government of Ontario]]\n|architect     = Leo Venchiarutti\n|director      = [[Ian Dejardin]] <small>(Executive Director)</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/about/board-staff/|title=Board and Staff|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|website=mcmichael.com|year=2018|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n|curator       = Sarah Milroy <small>(Chief Curator)</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/sarah-milroy/|title=Sarah Milroy|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|website=mcmichael.com|year=2018|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n|publictransit = \n|website       = {{URL|mcmichael.com}}\n}}\nThe '''McMichael Canadian Art Collection''' (MCAC) is an [[art museum]] in [[Vaughan]], [[Ontario]], Canada. The museum is located on a {{convert|100|acre|hectare|order=flip}} property in [[Kleinburg]], an unincorporated village in Vaughan. The property includes the museum's {{convert|85000|sqft|m2|order=flip}} main building, a sculpture garden, walking trails, and the cemetery for six members of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]].\n\nThe collection dates back to 1955, when Robert and Signe McMichael began to collect works from artists associated to the Group of Seven, exhibiting their works at their home in Kleinburg. In 1965, the McMichaels formally reached an agreement to donate their collection collection and their Kleinburg property to the [[Government of Ontario]] in order to establish an art museum. The institution was opened to the public as the '''McMichael Conservation Collection of Art''' in 1966. The museum was formally incorporated into the McMichael Canadian Art Collection in 1972. Although the museum was originally established with an institutional focus on the Group of Seven, the museum's mandate was later expanded to include contemporary Canadian art,  and art from [[indigenous Canadians]].\n\nThe museum's permanent collection includes over 6,500 works from Canadian artists. In addition to its permanent collections, the institution also serves as the custodians for the archives of works on paper by [[Inuit]] artists based in [[[[Kinngait]]]]. The museum organizes and hosts a number of [[travelling exhibition|travelling art exhibitions]], typically focused on [[Canadian art]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1951 Robert and Signe McMichael purchased a {{convert|10|acre|hectare}} plot of land in [[Kleinburg]], [[Ontario]].{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=183}} A home was subsequently built in 1954, with the McMichaels moving into the property.<ref name=canen>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/mcmichael-canadian-art-collection|title=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|date=4 March 2015|accessdate=29 November 2019|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=Historica Canada}}</ref> The McMichaels began acquiring works by artists of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]] for their personal collection, with the first being a painting by [[Tom Thomson]], acquired for [[Canadian dollar|C$]]250 in 1955.<ref name=g&m3>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/art-and-architecture/the-fraught-and-fierce-legacy-of-the-mcmichaels-cultural-vision/article27398658/|title=The fraught and fierce legacy of the McMichaels' cultural vision|date=20 November 2015|accessdate=7 December 2019|work=The Globe and Mail|publisher=The Woodbridge Company|last=Adams|first=James}}</ref> In 1962, the McMichaels acquired Tom Thomson's studio situated outside the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]] in [[Toronto]], and relocated it to their property to begin restorations on it.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=183}} By 1965, the McMichaels' personal collection contained 194 paintings either purchased or donated to them.<ref name=histoff>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/about/history/|title=Our History|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|year=2018|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Tom Thomson's studio at the McMichael Art Gallery (7376231718).jpg|thumb|The [[Tom Thomson]] Studio was relocated onto the property in 1962]]\nThe McMichaels began exhibiting their works on their Kleinburg property during the weekends, although growing number of visitors led the McMichaels to consider establishing a public a \"shrine\" dedicated to the Group of Seven.<ref name=canen/>{{sfn|Larsen|2009|p=210}} On 18 November 1965, the McMichaels and the [[Government of Ontario]] reached an agreement, where the McMichaels would donate the collection, and the property to the government, who would maintain the grounds, and maintain the \"spirit of the collection\".<ref name=canen/>{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=186}} As a part of the agreement, the McMichaels would maintain a degree of curatorial control, occupy two of the five seats in the museum's Board of Trustees, and permission to continue inhabiting the property, and be buried there.<ref name=g&m3/> The McMichaels continued to reside on the property until museum operations made it no longer possible; with the Government of Ontario providing them a home in [[Caledon, Ontario|Caledon]].<ref name=g&m3/>\n\nIn the months after the agreement was made, work was undertaken to re-purpose the property into an art museum, and prepare the exhibits for its collection.<ref name=g&m>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/art-and-architecture/mcmichael-canadian-art-collection-bets-big-on-past-for-50th-anniversary/article31387515/|title=McMichael Canadian Art Collection bets big on past for 50th anniversary|last=Adams|first=James|work=The Globe and Mail|publisher=The Woodbridge Company|date=12 August 2016|accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> The property was formally opened to the public on 8 July 1966 as the McMichael Conservation Collection of Art.<ref name=histoff/> Robert McMichael served as the museum's first director, holding the position until resigning in 1981.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=159}}\n\nIn 1968, Group of Seven member [[A. Y. Jackson]] suggested that the museum serve as the burial ground for himself, and other members of the group.{{sfn|Larsen|2009|p=210}} The proposal was later accepted by the museum, with a cemetery for Group of Seven members prepared on the property of the museum.{{sfn|Larsen|2009|p=210}} Shortly before his death, Jackson spent a significant portion of his time painting on the property,{{sfn|Larsen|2009|p=221}} and serving as the institution's [[artist-in-residence]].<ref name=canen/>\n\nIn 1969, the museum's mandate was amended to expand the scope of the museum's collection and scope to include works of similar nature that reflect the \"cultural heritage of Canada\"; with approval from Robert McMichael, and the [[Premier of Ontario]], [[John Robarts]].{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=164}} An increase in attendance rates, and its collection led to the institution being formally incorporated as a [[crown corporation]] of Ontario on 30 November 1972, when the ''McMichael Canadian Art Collection Act'' received [[Royal Assent]].{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=186}} In 1981, the museum's Board of Governors formally requested the province to amend the institution's governing act, so it is governed only by the 1972 act, and not by the 1965 agreement as well.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=165}} The following dispute led to Robert McMichael's resignation as the museum's director, and an amendment to the Act in 1982 that named McMichael as the institution's \"Founder, Director-Emeritus,\" and elevated the importance of indigenous Canadian works in its collection.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=165}}  \n\nIn the 1990s, the Robert McMichael challenged the Board and the province that it had deviated from its original mandate agreed upon. In ''McMichael v. Ontario'', the court originally ruled that changes to the museum's mandate should not have been permitted.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=184}} The decision was later overturned in the [[Court of Appeal for Ontario]] in 1997; and the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] dismissing an appeal to that ruling in 1998.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=168}} Failing to assert the original agreement through judicial means, the McMichaels successfully lobbied Member of Provincial Parliament [[Helen Johns]] to introduce a bill that would reassert it.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=168}} on 2 November 2000, Bill 112 received Royal Assent, amending the museum's mandate to better reflect the original mandate of showcasing Canadian landscape art, particularly works by the Group of Seven.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=168}}\n\nAfter proposals were submitted by the museum's Board of Directors, and the Fenwick family, the closest living relatives to the deceased McMichaels, Bill 118 received Royal Assent in June 2011, expanding the museum's mandate to include contemporary Canadian, and indigenous Canadian artists, in addition to artists associated with the Group of Seven.<ref name=2011amend>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2011/05/03/mcmichael_collection_legal_straitjacket_to_be_loosened.html|title=McMichael Collection: Legal straitjacket to be loosened|last=Whyte|first=Murray|publisher=Torstar Corporation|work=Toronto Star|date=3 May 2011}}</ref> The 2011 amendment to the governing act of the museum also removed art advisory committee, and restrictions to the museum's exhibition mandate.<ref name=2011amend/>\n\n==Grounds==\n[[File:Artistsstudio (7538256284).jpg|thumb|left|The grounds of the museum include the Pine Cottage building, which houses the institution's [[art studio]]]]\nThe McMichael Canadian Art Collection is situated in Kleinburg, an unincorporated village in [[Vaughan]], Ontario. The grounds of the museum is in a {{convert|100|acre|hectare|order=flip}} conservation area of the [[Humber River (Ontario)|Humber River]] Valley, and also serves as a [[floodplain]] for the area.<ref name=groundoff>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/visit/grounds-trail/|title=Grounds|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|website=mcmichael.com|accessdate=29 November 2019|year=2018}}</ref> The landscape itself was partially crafted by the McMichaels, and later the Government of Ontario, to help complement the museum's collection; with the McMichaels planting over 500 [[cedrus|cedar]] trees in the area to help recreate the landscapes typically painted by the Group of Seven.<ref>{{cite book|title=Museums and the Representation of Native Canadians: Negotiating the Borders of Culture|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=1999|last=McLoughlin|first=Moira|isbn=0-8153-2988-1|page=179}}</ref>\n\nBuildings located on the grounds includes the museum's main building, the Meeting House, Pine Cottage, and Tom Thomson's studio. Pine Cottage houses the institution's [[art studio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/event/painting-studio/2017-10-03/|title=Painting Studio|website=mcmichael.com|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|year=2018|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref> In addition to the structures, the grounds also contains a number of walking trails, a sculpture garden, and the McMichael cemetery.<ref name=groundoff/> The Ivan Eyre Sculpture Garden, and cemetery is located west of the buildings, with the sculpture garden exhibiting works from its permanent collection, and works on loan to the museum.<ref name=outdoor>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/collection/outdoor-art/|title=Outdoor Art|year=2018|accessdate=9 December 2019|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|website=mcmichael.com}}</ref> Six members of the Group of Seven are interred at the McMichael cemetery, including [[A. J. Casson]], [[Lawren Harris]], [[A. Y. Jackson]], [[Frank Johnston (artist)|Frank Johnston]], [[Arthur Lismer]], and [[Frederick Varley]].{{sfn|Larsen|2009|p=210}} \n\n===Main building===\nThe museum's main building was designed by Ontario-based architect, Leo Venchiarutti, and was completed in 1954.<ref name=g&m3/> The museum's main building was expanded several times in 1963, 1967, 1969, and 1972,<ref name=g&m3/> In 1981 to 1983, the museum's main building was closed to the public in order to facilitate a C$10.4 million renovation,<ref name=g&m3/> although no major work has been done to the building since than.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/wp-content/uploads/reports/McMichael_2015-16_Business_Plan.pdf|title=McMichael Canadian Art Collection 2015/16 Business Plan|website=mcmichael.com|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|accessdate=29 November 2019|year=2015}}</ref> The main building is approximately {{convert|85000|sqft|m2|order=flip}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/archive/en/2005/11/17/McGuinty-government-celebrates-40th-anniversary-of-McMichael-Canadian-Art-Collec.html|title=McGuinty government celebrates 40th anniversary of McMichael Canadian Art Collection|date=17 November 2005|accessdate=29 November 2019|publisher=Queen's Printer for Ontario|website=news.ontario.ca}}</ref> The main building was initially named ''Tapawingo'', allegedly meaning place of joy in either [[Haida language|Haida]] or [[Ojibwe language]].<ref name=g&m3/> \n[[File:Grand Hall (7551655754).jpg|thumb|The Grand Hall, an event space situated in museum's main building]]\nThe building has log and barn-board walls, and field-stone fireplaces in an effort to recreate the \"atmosphere\" of Canadian landscape art; in addition to a floor-to-glass ceiling windows that provide a view of the Humber River Valley.<ref name=canen/> The main building includes 14 viewing halls, a gift shop, and a restaurant.<ref name=canen/> The Western Canada Gallery in the main building contains a forty-foot-long [[cedrus|cedar]] bench, and red cedar arches, both of which contains images carved by [[Doug Cranmer]].{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=162}} However, the main building does not contain a large loading dock, preventing the institution from exhibiting large-scale [[installation art]]works in the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/visualarts/2016/06/11/at-the-mcmichael-an-anniversary-makes-peace-with-a-complicated-history.html|title=At the McMichael, an anniversary makes peace with a complicated history|publisher=Torstar Corporation|work=Toronto Star|last=Whyte|first=Murray|date=11 June 2016|accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Permanent collection==\nThe McMichael Canadian Art Collection is one of the only art museums whose permanent collection contains works exclusively by Canadian artists.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=161}} The permanent collection originates from the personal collection started by Robert and Signe McMichael in 1955; who later donated it to the province of Ontario in 1965.<ref name=canen/> At the time the McMichaels donated their collection, its contained 187 works.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=163}} The museum has since expanded this collection to include 6,500 works as of December 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/the-world-needs-canadian-art-i-m-going-to-give-it-to-them-says-new-head-of-mcmichael-gallery-1.4440251|title='The world needs Canadian art. I'm going to give it to them,' says new head of McMichael gallery|work=CBC News|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=26 December 2017|accessdate=7 December 2019|first=Nigel|last=Hunt}}</ref><ref name=coloff>{{cite web|url=https://mcmichael.com/collection|title=Collection|year=2018|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> The museum's permanent collection is organized into four collection areas, [[contemporary art]], [[First Nations]] art, the Group of Seven, and [[Inuit]] art.<ref name=coloff/> \n[[File:Ivan Eyre Yell, 2010 (14631616081).jpg|thumb|Sculptures by [[Ivan Eyre]] are exhibited at the sculpture garden]]\nAlthough the museum's original mandate placed a focus on Canadian landscape art, and the Group of Seven, it has since expanded to include other Canadian artists, including indigenous Canadians. As of 2011, the museum's mandate is to acquire and preserve works for the collection, by artists who have made a contribution to the development of Canadian art, with a focus on the Group of Seven and their contemporaries and on the indigenous Canadians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ontario.ca/laws/statute/S11016|title=McMichael Canadian Art Collection Amendment Act, 2011, S.O. 2011, c. 16 - Bill 188|publisher=Queen's Printer of Ontario|year=2019|accessdate=7 December 2019|website=ontario.ca}}</ref> In addition to artists associated with the Group of Seven, the museum's permanent collection also contains works from [[Cornelius Krieghoff]], [[David Milne (artist)|David Milne]], and [[Robert Pilot]].<ref name=g&m2>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/art-and-architecture/la-belle-province-takes-its-place-at-the-mcmichael-gallery-see-50-works-from-master-quebec-artists/article21594723/|title=La belle province takes its place at the McMichael gallery: See 50 works from master Quebec artists|publisher=The Woodbridge Company|work=The Globe and Mail|date=14 November 2014|accessdate=7 December 2019|last=Adams|first=James}}</ref> In November 2014, the museum was bequeathed 50 paintings from artists based in [[Quebec]]. [[French Canadian]] artists whose works are in the McMichael's permanent collection include [[Paul-\u00c9mile Borduas]], [[Marc-Aur\u00e8le de Foy Suzor-Cot\u00e9]], [[Marc-Aur\u00e8le Fortin]], [[Clarence Gagnon]], [[Rita Letendre]], [[Jean Paul Lemieux]], and [[Jean-Paul Riopelle]].<ref name=g&m2/>\n\nThe museum's contemporary collection was formally started in 2011, when the museum's mandate was expanded to include contemporary art,<ref name=contemp>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/collection/contemporary/|title=Contemporary Art|year=2018|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> although a number of works in the contemporary collection area were acquired by the institution prior to 2011.<ref name=g&m/> Canadian artists featured in the contemporary art collection includes [[Jack Bush]], [[Colleen Heslin]], [[Sarah Anne Johnson]], [[Terence Koh]], and [[Mary Pratt (painter)|Mary Pratt]].<ref name=contemp/> The museum also exhibits a number of sculptures within its outdoor sculpture garden, including nine sculptures by [[Ivan Eyre]].<ref name=outdoor/>\n\n===Indigenous Canadian art===\n[[File:A not so traditional totem (24055327648).jpg|thumb|upright|left|''When Cultures Meet'', by Don Yeomans, is a [[totem pole]] in the museum's collection]]\nThe museum was one of the first art museums to include works by indigenous Canadian in its collection.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=159}} In 1957, the McMichaels purchased their first work by a [[Haida people|Haida]] artist, [[Bill Reid]].{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=161}} The McMichaels' personal collection of Inuit stone carvings, and [[Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast|West Coast First Nations]] wood carvings, masks, and totem poles were donated to the province as a part of the 1965 agreement.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=163}} By 1981, approximately 42 per cent of works in the permanent collection were works by indigenous Canadian artists.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=161}}\n\nA number of indigenous artworks in the museum's collection was acquired between 1982 and 2000, when the museum's mandate was amended to include indigenous Canadian art into its definition of \"Canadian cultural heritage\".{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=159}} The museum's collection of works by indigenous Canadian was expanded to include contemporary artworks in the 1990s, with the museum establishing its first First Nations curator-in-residence in 1994.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=162}} In 2000, the museum's mandate was amended again, reverting the museum's focus to the Group of Seven and their contemporaries; resulting in the removal of most indigenous Canadian works from the museum's exhibits.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=171\u2013172}} Indigenous Canadian works in the collection remained in storage from 2000 to 2004, when works by indigenous Canadian artists were exhibited in the museum's viewing spaces again.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=172}} Indigenous Canadian art was reintroduced into the museum's mandate following an amendment to the institution's governing act in 2011.<ref name=2011amend/>\n\n==Library and archives==\nThe museum is also home to a library and archives whose holdings includes artist files, books, exhibition catalogues, letters, periodicals, and photographs. The museum's holdings specializes in the Group of Seven and indigenous Canadian art.<ref name=arclib>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/about/library-archives/|website=mcmichael.com|title=Library & Archives|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|year=2018|accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>  \n\nThe archives includes a number of specialized collections. The [[Arthur Lismer]] Collection was bequeathed to the museum by Lismer, and contains a number of documents and works from the 1890s to the late 1960s.<ref name=arclib/> The Lismer collection includes over 900 drawings, cartoons and sketches; 1300 original photographs; documents published by Lismer, as well as books.<ref name=arclib/> The Norman Hallendy Archives was completed in 2015 contains over 12,000 photographs by Hallendy, as well as audio and video recordings, maps, books, and research files on Inuit culture in southwest [[Baffin Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/norman-hallendy-archives/|title=The Norman Hallendy Archives|website=mcmichael.com|last=Morita|first=Linda|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|year=2018|accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe archives also houses over 100,000 drawings, prints, and sculptures from the West [[Kinngait Co-operative|Baffin Eskimo Co-operative Ltd.]], an [[artist collective]] based in [[Cape Dorset]], [[Nunavut]].<ref name=inuitoff>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/collection/inuit/|title=Inuit Art|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|year=2018|accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> The collective's works were moved to the McMichael's archive on a long-term loan in 1992, after a fire destroyed the collective's studio building<ref name=inuitoff/> The museum has digitized approximately works produced by the collective from 1959 to 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/travel/international-travel/exploring-south-baffin-islands-art-culture-and-wildlife|title=Exploring south Baffin Island\u2019s art, culture and wildlife|date=26 September 2019|accessdate=7 December 2019|last=Allford|first=Jennifer|work=Vancouver Sun|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n<gallery>\nFile:Herding Sheep 1910.jpg|[[Homer Watson]], ''Herding Sheep'', 1910\nFile:Thomson, In Algonquin Park.jpg|[[Tom Thomson]], ''In Algonquin Park'', Winter 1914\u201315\nFile:Franklin Carmichael - A Muskoka Road.jpg|[[Franklin Carmichael]], ''A Muskoka Road'', 1915\nFile:A. Y. Jackson - Cathedral at Ypres, Belgium.jpg|[[A. Y. Jackson]]. ''Cathedral at Ypres, Belgium'', 1917\nFile:Frank Johnston Sunset in the Bush.jpg|[[Frank Johnston (artist)|Frank Johnston]]. ''Sunset in the Bush'', 1918\nFile:J. E. H. MacDonald, Forest Wilderness 1921.jpg|[[J. E. H. MacDonald]], ''Forest Wilderness'', 1921\nFile:David Milne Painting Place Brown and Black.jpg|[[David Milne (artist)|David Milne]], ''Painting Place: Brown and Black'', {{circa|lk=no|1926}}\nFile:Emily Carr Shoreline 1936.jpg|[[Emily Carr]], ''Shoreline'', 1936\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notefoot}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of art museums]]\n*[[List of museums in Ontario]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|title=Aboriginal Canada Revisited|publisher=University of Ottawa Press|year=2008|isbn=0-7766-1776-1|last=Knopf|first=Kerstin|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=A.Y. Jackson: The Life of a Landscape Painter|publisher=Dundurn|year=2009|last=Larsen|first=Wayne|isbn=1-7707-0452-3|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|McMichael Gallery}}\n* {{official|http://www.mcmichael.com/}}\n\n{{Group of Seven}}\n{{Tom Thomson}}\n{{Vaughan}}\n\n[[Category:1965 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Art museums and galleries in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1965]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Vaughan]]\n[[Category:Museums in York Region]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox museum\n|name          = McMichael Canadian Art Collection\n|image         = Gallery New-Entrance Credit-Art2Print-Images (7538295154).jpg\n|caption       = Entrance to McMichael Canadian Art Collection's main building\n|coordinates   = {{coord|43.840776|-79.625205|display=inline,title}}\n|established   = {{start date and age|1965|7|8|df=yes}}{{notetag|The following date is when the institution was first established as a publicly-managed institution. The institution was opened to the public on 8 July 1966, and was formally incorporated into a crown corporation on 30 November 1972. The institution's permanent collection originates from the private collection of Robert and Signe McMichael, which was started in 1955.}}\n|location      = 10365 Islington Avenue,<br>[[Vaughan]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]\n|type          = [[Art museum]]\n|visitors      = 105,208{{notetag|Total attendance from April 2018 to March 2019.}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mcmichael.com/wp-content/uploads/Annual-Report-2018-19_ENG.pdf|title=Letter from the Executive Director|page=4|work=McMichael Canadian Art Collection 2018\u201319 Annual Report|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|year=2019}}</ref>\n|owner         = [[Government of Ontario]]\n|architect     = Leo Venchiarutti\n|director      = [[Ian Dejardin]] <small>(Executive Director)</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/about/board-staff/|title=Board and Staff|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|website=mcmichael.com|year=2018|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n|curator       = Sarah Milroy <small>(Chief Curator)</small><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/sarah-milroy/|title=Sarah Milroy|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|website=mcmichael.com|year=2018|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n|publictransit = \n|website       = {{URL|mcmichael.com}}\n}}\nThe '''McMichael Canadian Art Collection''' (MCAC) is an [[art museum]] in [[Vaughan]], [[Ontario]], Canada. The museum is located on a {{convert|100|acre|hectare|order=flip}} property in [[Kleinburg]], an unincorporated village in Vaughan. The property includes the museum's {{convert|85000|sqft|m2|order=flip}} main building, a sculpture garden, walking trails, and the cemetery for six members of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]].\n\nThe collection dates back to 1955, when Robert and Signe McMichael began to collect works from artists associated to the Group of Seven, exhibiting their works at their home in Kleinburg. In 1965, the McMichaels formally reached an agreement to donate their collection collection and their Kleinburg property to the [[Government of Ontario]] in order to establish an art museum. The institution was opened to the public as the '''McMichael Conservation Collection of Art''' in 1966. The museum was formally incorporated into the McMichael Canadian Art Collection in 1972. Although the museum was originally established with an institutional focus on the Group of Seven, the museum's mandate was later expanded to include contemporary Canadian art,  and art from [[indigenous Canadians]].\n\nThe museum's permanent collection includes over 6,500 works from Canadian artists. In addition to its permanent collections, the institution also serves as the custodians for the archives of works on paper by [[Inuit]] artists based in [[[[Kinngait]]]]. The museum organizes and hosts a number of [[travelling exhibition|travelling art exhibitions]], typically focused on [[Canadian art]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1951 Robert and Signe McMichael purchased a {{convert|10|acre|hectare}} plot of land in [[Kleinburg]], [[Ontario]].{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=183}} A home was subsequently built in 1954, with the McMichaels moving into the property.<ref name=canen>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/mcmichael-canadian-art-collection|title=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|date=4 March 2015|accessdate=29 November 2019|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=Historica Canada}}</ref> The McMichaels began acquiring works by artists of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]] for their personal collection, with the first being a painting by [[Tom Thomson]], acquired for [[Canadian dollar|C$]]250 in 1955.<ref name=g&m3>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/art-and-architecture/the-fraught-and-fierce-legacy-of-the-mcmichaels-cultural-vision/article27398658/|title=The fraught and fierce legacy of the McMichaels' cultural vision|date=20 November 2015|accessdate=7 December 2019|work=The Globe and Mail|publisher=The Woodbridge Company|last=Adams|first=James}}</ref> In 1962, the McMichaels acquired Tom Thomson's studio situated outside the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]] in [[Toronto]], and relocated it to their property to begin restorations on it.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=183}} By 1965, the McMichaels' personal collection contained 194 paintings either purchased or donated to them.<ref name=histoff>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/about/history/|title=Our History|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|year=2018|accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Tom Thomson's studio at the McMichael Art Gallery (7376231718).jpg|thumb|The [[Tom Thomson]] Studio was relocated onto the property in 1962]]\nThe McMichaels began exhibiting their works on their Kleinburg property during the weekends, although growing number of visitors led the McMichaels to consider establishing a public a \"shrine\" dedicated to the Group of Seven.<ref name=canen/>{{sfn|Larsen|2009|p=210}} On 18 November 1965, the McMichaels and the [[Government of Ontario]] reached an agreement, where the McMichaels would donate the collection, and the property to the government, who would maintain the grounds, and maintain the \"spirit of the collection\".<ref name=canen/>{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=186}} As a part of the agreement, the McMichaels would maintain a degree of curatorial control, occupy two of the five seats in the museum's Board of Trustees, and permission to continue inhabiting the property, and be buried there.<ref name=g&m3/> The McMichaels continued to reside on the property until museum operations made it no longer possible; with the Government of Ontario providing them a home [[Caledon, Ontario|Caledon]].<ref name=g&m3/>\n\nIn the months after the agreement was made, work was undertaken to re-purpose the property into an art museum, and prepare the exhibits for its collection.<ref name=g&m>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/art-and-architecture/mcmichael-canadian-art-collection-bets-big-on-past-for-50th-anniversary/article31387515/|title=McMichael Canadian Art Collection bets big on past for 50th anniversary|last=Adams|first=James|work=The Globe and Mail|publisher=The Woodbridge Company|date=12 August 2016|accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> The property was formally opened to the public on 8 July 1966 as the McMichael Conservation Collection of Art.<ref name=histoff/> Robert McMichael served as the museum's first director, holding the position until resigning in 1981.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=159}}\n\nIn 1968, Group of Seven member [[A. Y. Jackson]] suggested that the museum serve as the burial ground for himself, and other members of the group.{{sfn|Larsen|2009|p=210}} The proposal was later accepted by the museum, with a cemetery for Group of Seven members prepared on the property of the museum.{{sfn|Larsen|2009|p=210}} Shortly before his death, Jackson spent a significant portion of his time painting on the property,{{sfn|Larsen|2009|p=221}} and serving as the institution's [[artist-in-residence]].<ref name=canen/>\n\nIn 1969, the museum's mandate was amended to expand the scope of the museum's collection and scope to include works of similar nature that reflect the \"cultural heritage of Canada\"; with approval from Robert McMichael, and the [[Premier of Ontario]], [[John Robarts]].{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=164}} An increase in attendance rates, and its collection led to the institution being formally incorporated as a [[crown corporation]] of Ontario on 30 November 1972, when the ''McMichael Canadian Art Collection Act'' received [[Royal Assent]].{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=186}} In 1981, the museum's Board of Governors formally requested the province to amend the institution's governing act, so it is governed only by the 1972 act, and not by the 1965 agreement as well.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=165}} The following dispute led to Robert McMichael's resignation as the museum's director, and an amendment to the Act in 1982 that named McMichael as the institution's \"Founder, Director-Emeritus,\" and elevated the importance of indigenous Canadian works in its collection.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=165}}  \n\nIn the 1990s, the Robert McMichael challenged the Board and the province that it had deviated from its original mandate agreed upon. In ''McMichael v. Ontario'', the court originally ruled that changes to the museum's mandate should not have been permitted.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=184}} The decision was later overturned in the [[Court of Appeal for Ontario]] in 1997; and the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] dismissing an appeal to that ruling in 1998.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=168}} Failing to assert the original agreement through judicial means, the McMichaels successfully lobbied Member of Provincial Parliament [[Helen Johns]] to introduce a bill that would reassert it.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=168}} on 2 November 2000, Bill 112 received Royal Assent, amending the museum's mandate to better reflect the original mandate of showcasing Canadian landscape art, particularly works by the Group of Seven.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=168}}\n\nAfter proposals were submitted by the museum's Board of Directors, and the Fenwick family, the closest living relatives to the deceased McMichaels, Bill 118 received Royal Assent in June 2011, expanding the museum's mandate to include contemporary Canadian, and indigenous Canadian artists, in addition to artists associated with the Group of Seven.<ref name=2011amend>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2011/05/03/mcmichael_collection_legal_straitjacket_to_be_loosened.html|title=McMichael Collection: Legal straitjacket to be loosened|last=Whyte|first=Murray|publisher=Torstar Corporation|work=Toronto Star|date=3 May 2011}}</ref> The 2011 amendment to the governing act of the museum also removed art advisory committee, and restrictions to the museum's exhibition mandate.<ref name=2011amend/>\n\n==Grounds==\n[[File:Artistsstudio (7538256284).jpg|thumb|left|The grounds of the museum include the Pine Cottage building, which houses the institution's [[art studio]]]]\nThe McMichael Canadian Art Collection is situated in Kleinburg, an unincorporated village in [[Vaughan]], Ontario. The grounds of the museum is in a {{convert|100|acre|hectare|order=flip}} conservation area of the [[Humber River (Ontario)|Humber River]] Valley, and also serves as a [[floodplain]] for the area.<ref name=groundoff>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/visit/grounds-trail/|title=Grounds|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|website=mcmichael.com|accessdate=29 November 2019|year=2018}}</ref> The landscape itself was partially crafted by the McMichaels, and later the Government of Ontario, to help complement the museum's collection; with the McMichaels planting over 500 [[cedrus|cedar]] trees in the area to help recreate the landscapes typically painted by the Group of Seven.<ref>{{cite book|title=Museums and the Representation of Native Canadians: Negotiating the Borders of Culture|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=1999|last=McLoughlin|first=Moira|isbn=0-8153-2988-1|page=179}}</ref>\n\nBuildings located on the grounds includes the museum's main building, the Meeting House, Pine Cottage, and Tom Thomson's studio. Pine Cottage houses the institution's [[art studio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/event/painting-studio/2017-10-03/|title=Painting Studio|website=mcmichael.com|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|year=2018|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref> In addition to the structures, the grounds also contains a number of walking trails, a sculpture garden, and the McMichael cemetery.<ref name=groundoff/> The Ivan Eyre Sculpture Garden, and cemetery is located west of the buildings, with the sculpture garden exhibiting works from its permanent collection, and works on loan to the museum.<ref name=outdoor>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/collection/outdoor-art/|title=Outdoor Art|year=2018|accessdate=9 December 2019|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|website=mcmichael.com}}</ref> Six members of the Group of Seven are interred at the McMichael cemetery, including [[A. J. Casson]], [[Lawren Harris]], [[A. Y. Jackson]], [[Frank Johnston (artist)|Frank Johnston]], [[Arthur Lismer]], and [[Frederick Varley]].{{sfn|Larsen|2009|p=210}} \n\n===Main building===\nThe museum's main building was designed by Ontario-based architect, Leo Venchiarutti, and was completed in 1954.<ref name=g&m3/> The museum's main building was expanded several times in 1963, 1967, 1969, and 1972,<ref name=g&m3/> In 1981 to 1983, the museum's main building was closed to the public in order to facilitate a C$10.4 million renovation,<ref name=g&m3/> although no major work has been done to the building since than.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/wp-content/uploads/reports/McMichael_2015-16_Business_Plan.pdf|title=McMichael Canadian Art Collection 2015/16 Business Plan|website=mcmichael.com|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|accessdate=29 November 2019|year=2015}}</ref> The main building is approximately {{convert|85000|sqft|m2|order=flip}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.ontario.ca/archive/en/2005/11/17/McGuinty-government-celebrates-40th-anniversary-of-McMichael-Canadian-Art-Collec.html|title=McGuinty government celebrates 40th anniversary of McMichael Canadian Art Collection|date=17 November 2005|accessdate=29 November 2019|publisher=Queen's Printer for Ontario|website=news.ontario.ca}}</ref> The main building was initially named ''Tapawingo'', allegedly meaning place of joy in either [[Haida language|Haida]] or [[Ojibwe language]].<ref name=g&m3/> \n[[File:Grand Hall (7551655754).jpg|thumb|The Grand Hall, an event space situated in museum's main building]]\nThe building has log and barn-board walls, and field-stone fireplaces in an effort to recreate the \"atmosphere\" of Canadian landscape art; in addition to a floor-to-glass ceiling windows that provide a view of the Humber River Valley.<ref name=canen/> The main building includes 14 viewing halls, a gift shop, and a restaurant.<ref name=canen/> The Western Canada Gallery in the main building contains a forty-foot-long [[cedrus|cedar]] bench, and red cedar arches, both of which contains images carved by [[Doug Cranmer]].{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=162}} However, the main building does not contain a large loading dock, preventing the institution from exhibiting large-scale [[installation art]]works in the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/visualarts/2016/06/11/at-the-mcmichael-an-anniversary-makes-peace-with-a-complicated-history.html|title=At the McMichael, an anniversary makes peace with a complicated history|publisher=Torstar Corporation|work=Toronto Star|last=Whyte|first=Murray|date=11 June 2016|accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Permanent collection==\nThe McMichael Canadian Art Collection is one of the only art museums whose permanent collection contains works exclusively by Canadian artists.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=161}} The permanent collection originates from the personal collection started by Robert and Signe McMichael in 1955; who later donated it to the province of Ontario in 1965.<ref name=canen/> At the time the McMichaels donated their collection, its contained 187 works.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=163}} The museum has since expanded this collection to include 6,500 works as of December 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/the-world-needs-canadian-art-i-m-going-to-give-it-to-them-says-new-head-of-mcmichael-gallery-1.4440251|title='The world needs Canadian art. I'm going to give it to them,' says new head of McMichael gallery|work=CBC News|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|date=26 December 2017|accessdate=7 December 2019|first=Nigel|last=Hunt}}</ref><ref name=coloff>{{cite web|url=https://mcmichael.com/collection|title=Collection|year=2018|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> The museum's permanent collection is organized into four collection areas, [[contemporary art]], [[First Nations]] art, the Group of Seven, and [[Inuit]] art.<ref name=coloff/> \n[[File:Ivan Eyre Yell, 2010 (14631616081).jpg|thumb|Sculptures by [[Ivan Eyre]] are exhibited at the sculpture garden]]\nAlthough the museum's original mandate placed a focus on Canadian landscape art, and the Group of Seven, it has since expanded to include other Canadian artists, including indigenous Canadians. As of 2011, the museum's mandate is to acquire and preserve works for the collection, by artists who have made a contribution to the development of Canadian art, with a focus on the Group of Seven and their contemporaries and on the indigenous Canadians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ontario.ca/laws/statute/S11016|title=McMichael Canadian Art Collection Amendment Act, 2011, S.O. 2011, c. 16 - Bill 188|publisher=Queen's Printer of Ontario|year=2019|accessdate=7 December 2019|website=ontario.ca}}</ref> In addition to artists associated with the Group of Seven, the museum's permanent collection also contains works from [[Cornelius Krieghoff]], [[David Milne (artist)|David Milne]], and [[Robert Pilot]].<ref name=g&m2>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/art-and-architecture/la-belle-province-takes-its-place-at-the-mcmichael-gallery-see-50-works-from-master-quebec-artists/article21594723/|title=La belle province takes its place at the McMichael gallery: See 50 works from master Quebec artists|publisher=The Woodbridge Company|work=The Globe and Mail|date=14 November 2014|accessdate=7 December 2019|last=Adams|first=James}}</ref> In November 2014, the museum was bequeathed 50 paintings from artists based in [[Quebec]]. [[French Canadian]] artists whose works are in the McMichael's permanent collection include [[Paul-\u00c9mile Borduas]], [[Marc-Aur\u00e8le de Foy Suzor-Cot\u00e9]], [[Marc-Aur\u00e8le Fortin]], [[Clarence Gagnon]], [[Rita Letendre]], [[Jean Paul Lemieux]], and [[Jean-Paul Riopelle]].<ref name=g&m2/>\n\nThe museum's contemporary collection was formally started in 2011, when the museum's mandate was expanded to include contemporary art,<ref name=contemp>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/collection/contemporary/|title=Contemporary Art|year=2018|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> although a number of works in the contemporary collection area were acquired by the institution prior to 2011.<ref name=g&m/> Canadian artists featured in the contemporary art collection includes [[Jack Bush]], [[Colleen Heslin]], [[Sarah Anne Johnson]], [[Terence Koh]], and [[Mary Pratt (painter)|Mary Pratt]].<ref name=contemp/> The museum also exhibits a number of sculptures within its outdoor sculpture garden, including nine sculptures by [[Ivan Eyre]].<ref name=outdoor/>\n\n===Indigenous Canadian art===\n[[File:A not so traditional totem (24055327648).jpg|thumb|upright|left|''When Cultures Meet'', by Don Yeomans, is a [[totem pole]] in the museum's collection]]\nThe museum was one of the first art museums to include works by indigenous Canadian in its collection.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=159}} In 1957, the McMichaels purchased their first work by a [[Haida people|Haida]] artist, [[Bill Reid]].{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=161}} The McMichaels' personal collection of Inuit stone carvings, and [[Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast|West Coast First Nations]] wood carvings, masks, and totem poles were donated to the province as a part of the 1965 agreement.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=163}} By 1981, approximately 42 per cent of works in the permanent collection were works by indigenous Canadian artists.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=161}}\n\nA number of indigenous artworks in the museum's collection was acquired between 1982 and 2000, when the museum's mandate was amended to include indigenous Canadian art into its definition of \"Canadian cultural heritage\".{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=159}} The museum's collection of works by indigenous Canadian was expanded to include contemporary artworks in the 1990s, with the museum establishing its first First Nations curator-in-residence in 1994.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=162}} In 2000, the museum's mandate was amended again, reverting the museum's focus to the Group of Seven and their contemporaries; resulting in the removal of most indigenous Canadian works from the museum's exhibits.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=171\u2013172}} Indigenous Canadian works in the collection remained in storage from 2000 to 2004, when works by indigenous Canadian artists were exhibited in the museum's viewing spaces again.{{sfn|Knopf|2008|p=172}} Indigenous Canadian art was reintroduced into the museum's mandate following an amendment to the institution's governing act in 2011.<ref name=2011amend/>\n\n==Library and archives==\nThe museum is also home to a library and archives whose holdings includes artist files, books, exhibition catalogues, letters, periodicals, and photographs. The museum's holdings specializes in the Group of Seven and indigenous Canadian art.<ref name=arclib>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/about/library-archives/|website=mcmichael.com|title=Library & Archives|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|year=2018|accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>  \n\nThe archives includes a number of specialized collections. The [[Arthur Lismer]] Collection was bequeathed to the museum by Lismer, and contains a number of documents and works from the 1890s to the late 1960s.<ref name=arclib/> The Lismer collection includes over 900 drawings, cartoons and sketches; 1300 original photographs; documents published by Lismer, as well as books.<ref name=arclib/> The Norman Hallendy Archives was completed in 2015 contains over 12,000 photographs by Hallendy, as well as audio and video recordings, maps, books, and research files on Inuit culture in southwest [[Baffin Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/norman-hallendy-archives/|title=The Norman Hallendy Archives|website=mcmichael.com|last=Morita|first=Linda|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|year=2018|accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe archives also houses over 100,000 drawings, prints, and sculptures from the West [[Kinngait Co-operative|Baffin Eskimo Co-operative Ltd.]], an [[artist collective]] based in [[Cape Dorset]], [[Nunavut]].<ref name=inuitoff>{{cite web|url=http://mcmichael.com/collection/inuit/|title=Inuit Art|publisher=McMichael Canadian Art Collection|year=2018|accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> The collective's works were moved to the McMichael's archive on a long-term loan in 1992, after a fire destroyed the collective's studio building<ref name=inuitoff/> The museum has digitized approximately works produced by the collective from 1959 to 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vancouversun.com/travel/international-travel/exploring-south-baffin-islands-art-culture-and-wildlife|title=Exploring south Baffin Island\u2019s art, culture and wildlife|date=26 September 2019|accessdate=7 December 2019|last=Allford|first=Jennifer|work=Vancouver Sun|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n<gallery>\nFile:Herding Sheep 1910.jpg|[[Homer Watson]], ''Herding Sheep'', 1910\nFile:Thomson, In Algonquin Park.jpg|[[Tom Thomson]], ''In Algonquin Park'', Winter 1914\u201315\nFile:Franklin Carmichael - A Muskoka Road.jpg|[[Franklin Carmichael]], ''A Muskoka Road'', 1915\nFile:A. Y. Jackson - Cathedral at Ypres, Belgium.jpg|[[A. Y. Jackson]]. ''Cathedral at Ypres, Belgium'', 1917\nFile:Frank Johnston Sunset in the Bush.jpg|[[Frank Johnston (artist)|Frank Johnston]]. ''Sunset in the Bush'', 1918\nFile:J. E. H. MacDonald, Forest Wilderness 1921.jpg|[[J. E. H. MacDonald]], ''Forest Wilderness'', 1921\nFile:David Milne Painting Place Brown and Black.jpg|[[David Milne (artist)|David Milne]], ''Painting Place: Brown and Black'', {{circa|lk=no|1926}}\nFile:Emily Carr Shoreline 1936.jpg|[[Emily Carr]], ''Shoreline'', 1936\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notefoot}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of art museums]]\n*[[List of museums in Ontario]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|title=Aboriginal Canada Revisited|publisher=University of Ottawa Press|year=2008|isbn=0-7766-1776-1|last=Knopf|first=Kerstin|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=A.Y. Jackson: The Life of a Landscape Painter|publisher=Dundurn|year=2009|last=Larsen|first=Wayne|isbn=1-7707-0452-3|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|McMichael Gallery}}\n* {{official|http://www.mcmichael.com/}}\n\n{{Group of Seven}}\n{{Tom Thomson}}\n{{Vaughan}}\n\n[[Category:1965 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Art museums and galleries in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Art museums established in 1965]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Vaughan]]\n[[Category:Museums in York Region]]\n", "name_user": "Joan arden murray", "label": "safe", "comment": "word added to read better", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/McMichael_Canadian_Art_Collection"}
