|Florida Tech]]\n | overall      = 8\u20134\n | conference   = 5\u20133\n | confstanding = T\u20133rd\n | bowlname     = [[NCAA Division II Football Championship|NCAA Division II First Round]]\n | bowloutcome  = L\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[2019 NCAA Division II football season|2019]]\n | name         = [[2019 Florida Tech Panthers football team|Florida Tech]]\n | overall      = 5\u20136\n | conference   = 3\u20135\n | confstanding = T\u20136th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Florida Tech\n | overall    = 44\u201335\n | confrecord = 25\u201326\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 70\u201349\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n | polltype = \n | legend   = no\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.floridatechsports.com/coaches.aspx?rc=146&path=football Florida Tech profile]\n\n{{Indiana State Sycamores quarterback navbox}}\n{{Rose-Hulman Fightin' Engineers football coach navbox}}\n{{Florida Tech Panthers football coach navbox}}\n{{Gulf South Conference football coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Englehart, Steve}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Florida Tech Panthers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Indiana State Sycamores football coaches]]\n[[Category:Indiana State Sycamores football players]]\n[[Category:Northeastern State RiverHawks football coaches]]\n[[Category:Rose-Hulman Fightin' Engineers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Terre Haute, Indiana]]\n\n{{Amfoot-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Steve Englehart\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| current_title = [[Head coach]]\n| current_team = [[Florida Tech Panthers football|Florida Tech]]\n| current_conference = [[Gulf South Conference|GSC]]\n| current_record = 44\u201335\n| contract = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1977|4|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Terre Haute, Indiana]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1996\u20131999\n| player_team1 = [[Indiana State Sycamores football|Indiana State]]\n| player_positions = [[Quarterback]]\n| coach_years1 = 2002\u20132005\n| coach_team1 = [[Rose-Hulman Fightin' Engineers football|Rose-Hulman]] ([[Offensive coordinator|OC]]/QB)\n| coach_years2 = 2006\u20132009\n| coach_team2 = [[Rose-Hulman Fightin' Engineers football|Rose-Hulman]]\n| coach_years3 = 2010\n| coach_team3 = [[Indiana State Sycamores football|Indiana State]] (OC/QB)\n| coach_years4 = 2011\u2013present\n| coach_team4 = [[Florida Tech Panthers football|Florida Tech]]\n| overall_record = 70\u201349\n| bowl_record = 1\u20130\n| tournament_record = 0\u20132 (NCAA D-II playoffs)\n| championships = \n| awards = 2\u00d7 [[Gulf South Conference|GSC]] Coach of the Year (2014, 2015)\n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Steve Englehart'''  (born April 11, 1977) is an [[American football]] coach and former player.  He is the head football coach at the [[Florida Institute of Technology]], a position he has held since the program's inception; Florida Tech began play in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.floridatechsports.com/athletics/directory/731/steve-englehart/|title=Staff directory: Steve Englehart|publisher=Florida Tech Athletics|access-date=May 25, 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730100652/http://www.floridatechsports.com/athletics/directory/731/steve-englehart/|archive-date=July 30, 2016|df=}}</ref>  Englehart was the head football coach at [[Rose-Hulman Institute of Technology]] from 2006 to 2009. After spending the 2010 season as the offensive coordinator and quarterbacks coach at [[Indiana State Sycamores football|Indiana State]], Englehart was hired as the first head coach in Florida Tech history on June 15, 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title= FLORIDA TECH NAMES ENGLEHART HEAD FOOTBALL COACH|url=https://floridatechsports.com/news/2011/6/15/6_15_2011%20_3325.aspx?path=football|accessdate=6 January 2019|publisher=Florida Institute of Technology}}</ref> Englehart won the [[Gulf South Conference]] Coach of The Year award for the 2014 season after leading Florida Tech to a winning record in just its second season <ref>{{cite news|title= GSC Announces 2014 All-Conference Football Honors|url=https://gscsports.org/news/2014/11/18/FB_1118140620.aspx?path=football|accessdate=6 January 2019|publisher=Gulf South Conference}}</ref> and again in 2015 as the Panthers challenged for a playoff spot with a 7-4 record, including wins over #5 Delta State and #1 West Georgia.<ref>{{cite news|title= GSC Announces All-Conference Football Honors|url=https://gscsports.org/news/2015/11/17/FB_1117151848.aspx?path=football|accessdate=6 January 2019|publisher=Gulf South Conference}}</ref> Florida Tech has recorded winning records in four of Englehart's seven seasons, including playoff berths in 2016 and 2018.\n\n==Personal life==\nEnglehart was born in [[Terre Haute, Indiana]], to Steve Englehart and his wife, Debbie. Steve graduated from Terre Haute North High School and later married Carrie May on May 13, 2000. They have three children together, two sons, Caden and Ty, and a daughter, Lila.\n\nEnglehart graduated from Indiana State University in Terrehaute, where he played [[quarterback]] for the football team under head coaches [[Dennis Raetz]] and [[Tim McGuire]].\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Rose-Hulman Fightin' Engineers football|Rose-Hulman Fightin' Engineers]]\n | conf      = [[Heartland Collegiate Athletic Conference]]\n | startyear = 2006\n | endyear   = 2009\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[2006 NCAA Division II football season|2006]]\n | name         = Rose-Hulman\n | overall      