\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[2014 NCAA Division II football season|2014]]\n | name         = [[2014 Florida Tech Panthers football team|Florida Tech]]\n | overall      = 6\u20135\n | conference   = 3\u20134\n | confstanding = 5th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[2015 NCAA Division II football season|2015]]\n | name         = Florida Tech\n | overall      = 7\u20134\n | conference   = 5\u20132\n | confstanding = T\u20132nd\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[2016 NCAA Division II football season|2016]]\n | name         = [[2016 Florida Tech Panthers football team|Florida Tech]]\n | overall      = 8\u20133\n | conference   = 5\u20132\n | confstanding = 4th\n | bowlname     = [[NCAA Division II Football Championship|NCAA Division II First Round]]\n | bowloutcome  = L\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[2017 NCAA Division II football season|2017]]\n | name         = [[2017 Florida Tech Panthers football team|Florida Tech]]\n | overall      = 5\u20136\n | conference   = 3\u20135\n | confstanding = 7th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[2018 NCAA Division II football season|2018]]\n | name         = [[2018 Florida Tech Panthers football team|Florida Tech]]\n | overall      = 8\u20134\n | conference   = 5\u20133\n | confstanding = T\u20133rd\n | bowlname     = [[NCAA Division II Football Championship|NCAA Division II First Round]]\n | bowloutcome  = L\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[2019 NCAA Division II football season|2019]]\n | name         = [[2019 Florida Tech Panthers football team|Florida Tech]]\n | overall      = 5\u20136\n | conference   = 3\u20135\n | confstanding = T\u20136th\n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Florida Tech\n | overall    = 44\u201335\n | confrecord = 25\u201326\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 70\u201349\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n | polltype = \n | legend   = no\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.floridatechsports.com/coaches.aspx?rc=146&path=football Florida Tech profile]\n\n{{Indiana State Sycamores quarterback navbox}}\n{{Rose-Hulman Fightin' Engineers football coach navbox}}\n{{Florida Tech Panthers football coach navbox}}\n{{Gulf South Conference football coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Englehart, Steve}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Florida Tech Panthers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Indiana State Sycamores football coaches]]\n[[Category:Indiana State Sycamores football players]]\n[[Category:Northeastern State RiverHawks football coaches]]\n[[Category:Rose-Hulman Fightin' Engineers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Terre Haute, Indiana]]\n\n{{Amfoot-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "47.30.164.36", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Englehart_(American_football)"}
{"title_page": "Tha Doggfather", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Tha Doggfather\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Snoop Dogg|Snoop Doggy Dogg]]\n| cover      = Thadoggfather.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 12, 1996\n| recorded   = February \u2013 October 1996\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = <!--These genres are sourced in the body of the page. Do not add unsourced genres -->\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Mafioso rap]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Mickey Hess|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bXy2wTEsbCsC&pg=PA377&lpg=PA377&dq|title=Icons of hip hop : an encyclopedia of the movement, music, and ..., Volume 2|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]|year=2007|accessdate=2019-11-18}}</ref>\n* [[G-funk]]\n| length     = 74:13\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Death Row Records|Death Row]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Suge Knight]] <small>([[Executive producer#Music|exec]].)</small>\n* [[DJ Pooh]]\n* [[Daz Dillinger]]\n* [[Soopafly]]\n* [[L.T. Hutton]]\n* [[Sam Sneed]]\n* Arkim & Flair}}\n| prev_title = [[Doggystyle]]\n| prev_year  = 1993\n| next_title = [[Da Game Is to Be Sold, Not to Be Told]]\n| next_year  = 1998\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Tha Doggfather\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Snoop's Upside Ya Head]]\n | single1date = September 14, 1996\n | single2     = [[Vapors (song)#Snoop Doggy Dogg version|Vapors]]\n | single2date = April 8, 1997\n | single3     = [[Doggfather]]\n | single3date = August 26, 1997\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Tha Doggfather''''' is the second [[studio album]] by American rapper [[Snoop Dogg|Snoop Doggy Dogg]]. It was released on November 12, 1996, by [[Death Row Records]] and [[Interscope Records]]. After the success of his debut album ''[[Doggystyle]]'' (1993), Snoop was charged with murder and in 1995, spent time preparing for the case that went to trial. In February 1996, he was cleared of all charges and began working on his second album without [[Dr. Dre]] providing work as a [[record producer]]. This was Snoop's final album on Death Row Records under his name of ''Snoop Doggy Dogg''. Recording sessions took place from February 1996 to October 1996, with [[Suge Knight]] filling in as the [[Executive producer#Music|executive producer]] on the album, alongside the additional production from several [[record producer]]s such as [[DJ Pooh]], [[Daz Dillinger]], [[Soopafly]] and [[L.T. Hutton]]; as well as [[guest appearance]]s from [[Charlie Wilson (musician)|Charlie Wilson]], [[Kurupt|Kurupt tha Kingpin]], [[Tray Dee]] and [[Warren G]], among others.\n\nThe album debuted at number one during the week of November 12, 1996, selling over 420,000 copies, but it failed to match the commercial success of ''Doggystyle''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EQoEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA22&dq=snoop+dogg+bubbling+under&hl=pt-BR&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwilscbQ97XNAhXFh5AKHQIPAaIQ6AEIJzAB#v=onepage&q=snoop%20dogg%20bubbling%20under&f=false |title=Billboard magazine - August 22, 1998 |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=June 20, 2016}}</ref> [[Dr. Dre]] had left Death Row to his partner [[Suge Knight]], who was indicted for racketeering by the end of 1996. ''Tha Doggfather'' was also released only one week after another Death Row release, the first posthumous album by [[Tupac Shakur|2Pac]], ''[[The Don Killuminati: The 7 Day Theory]]'', which debuted at number one. Consequently, Snoop's second album stalled at sales of two million copies.\n\n== Background ==\nIn 1992, Snoop Dogg featured on the album ''[[The Chronic]]'' by close friend Dr. Dre, which was a great success.\n\nIn 1993, Snoop and Dr. Dre began work on ''Doggystyle'' which was also very popular and acclaimed. During the recording of ''Doggystyle'' Snoop became a defendant in a murder case which saw his acquittal shortly before this album was released, which led him to no longer live the \"gangsta\" lifestyle he portrayed in his records.\n\nDr. Dre, who was Death Row Records' in-house producer, had left earlier in 1996 to start [[Aftermath Entertainment|his own label]], which led Snoop's first cousin Daz Dillinger to become Death Row's head producer; he worked on this record. The [[Murder of Tupac Shakur|murder of Snoop's close friend and fellow rapper, label-mate Tupac Shakur]] in September 1996 also weighed on him heavily; Shakur appears on the closing track \"Outro\", under the name \"Makaveli\", which he began using a short while before his death. \n\n==Release==\n''Tha Doggfather'' charted at number one on both the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] charts. To date, the album sold two million copies in the United States and sold better internationally than its predecessor, \"Doggystyle\" (1993).\n\n==Music==\n\n===Production===\nDuring the departure of Dr. Dre from Death Row Records, the majority of this album was produced and mixed by [[DJ Pooh]]. In addition to DJ Pooh, Daz Dillinger and several other producers contributed to this album. In 1996, in an interview with [[Rap City (BET program)|Rap City]], Snoop Dogg revealed that he had been working with Dr. Dre for this album; however, he had been prevented from doing so by Suge Knight. The album samples songs such as \"It's Like That\" performed by [[Run-D.M.C.]], \"[[Vapors (song)|Vapors]]\" performed by [[Biz Markie]], \"More Bounce to the Ounce\" performed by [[Zapp & Roger]], and \"[[Oops Upside Your Head]]\" performed by [[The Gap Band]]. The Doggfather also marked the debut of Snoop Dogg as a [[record producer]] on the track \"(O.J.) Wake Up\". Snoop Dogg also was beginning to be acknowledged on how to play [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]] by a high-profile producer named [[L.T. Hutton]], who led a hand providing some production on that track as well.<ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=asSDVUq8HaY |title=Snoop Dogg Rap City Interview (Part 2) |publisher=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=2011-10-01}}</ref>\n\nThe illustration on the back cover of the CD was done by Joe Cool, the same artist who did the front cover of Snoop's previous album ''Doggystyle''.\n\n===Lyrics===\nCompared to Doggystyle, the lyrics are much less violent and controversial. On ''Tha Doggfather'', Snoop Dogg wanted to present a more positive image in his lyrics, a reflection of his maturation as an artist and as a new father.<ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Er-CVjntHlA |title=Snoop Dogg Rap City Interview (Part 1) |publisher=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=2011-10-01}}</ref> On December 3, 2006, in an interview with [[Vh1]], Snoop Dogg revealed the differences between ''Doggystyle'' and ''Tha Doggfather'', stating, \"I think ''Tha Doggfather'' was a rebirth of me, as far as me being more positive on what I was tryin' to say and, you know, tryin' to live the life through my music, instead of me just livin' my life, tryin' to show people that my life... wasn't like my music...I'm not gonna glorify none of this negativity that Death Row wanted me to do. I'm gonna bring a positive side of music.\" Although his new lyrical direction was met with mixed feelings from fans and critics alike, Snoop Dogg still thinks of the album as a success: \"I enjoyed it and everywhere I go around the world people, you know, I sign more Doggfather records than any other record I put out. That's the one I sign the most and I'm proud at the thang I did and the thang is... sometimes you can outgrow your fans\".<ref>{{cite video |url=http://www.vh1.com/video/misc/122939/on-the-doggfather.jhtml#artist=1133 |title=On \"Tha Doggfather\" by Snoop Dogg |publisher=[[VH1]] |accessdate={{date|2011-10-01|mdy}}}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical reaction ===\n{{Album reviews\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]] \n|rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r244077|tab=review |label=\"Snoop Dogg: ''Tha Doggfather'' |first=Stephen Thomas |last=Erlewine |accessdate={{date|2011-10-01|mdy}}}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n|rev2Score = B+<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,295271,00.html |title=Music Review: 'Tha Doggfather' (1996) |first=J.D. |last=Considine |authorlink=J.D. Considine |date={{date|Nov 29, 1996|mdy}} |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |issue=#355 |publisher=Time |issn=1049-0434 |accessdate={{date|2011-10-01|mdy}}}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Muzik]]''\n|rev3Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.cduniverse.com/productinfo.asp?pid=1631897&style=music&cart=358537095&BAB=M |title='Tha Doggfather' Review |date=January 1997 |page=118 |magazine=[[Muzik]] |publisher=IPC Media |issn=1358-541X |accessdate={{date|2011-10-01|mdy}}}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' \n|rev4Score = {{Rating|2.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-12-08/entertainment/ca-6878_1_gift-guide-stars |title=Making a list? Checking it twice? Here are some guidelines to keep befuddled spouses, parents of teenagers and others on the right track. |date=December 8, 1996 |first=Cheo Hodari |last=Coker |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=Tribune Company |issn=0458-3035 |oclc=3638237 |accessdate={{date|2011-10-01|mdy}}}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The New York Times]]''\n|rev5Score = favorable<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/11/26/arts/machismo-in-rap-atop-the-charts.html | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | first=Jon | last=Pareles | title=Machismo In Rap Atop The Charts | date=November 26, 1996}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n|rev6Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref>{{cite book | author1= Nathan Brackett | author2= Christian David Hoard| title = The new Rolling Stone album guide | publisher = Simon & Schuster | location = New York | year = 2004 | isbn = 978-0-7432-0169-8 |url=https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac | url-access= registration | page= [https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/n768 755] | quote= doggystyle snoop rolling stone. |accessdate={{date|2012-06-02|mdy}}}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n|rev7Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.google.com/archivesearch?q=snoop+dogg+%22tha+doggfather%22+source%3A%22USA%22+source%3A%22Today%22&btnG=Search+Archives&num=10&hl=en&scoring=a |title=The return of N.W.A. Album ahead after attitude adjustments, Dogg addition |first=Steve |last=Jones |date={{date|Mar 23, 2000|mdy}} |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |publisher=Gannett |issn=0734-7456}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe album received generally moderate reviews from critics and fans at the time of its release. In a February issue of [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] magazine, Dr. Dre stated his feelings on the album and said \"But to be perfectly honest, I don't like Snoop's new album. And it has nothing to do with me not working him, because I'm just like everybody else: I like it, or I don't. The first time I heard the single, I was grooving to it, but then I really started to get into the production and how it was sounding, you know? The first time you hear some shit, you just listen to it to get your groove on, but after that, I start breaking songs down. There's really nothing that was said on there that hasn't been said 50 times before.\"<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wF1pZCI8MZYC&pg=PA50&dq=snoop+dogg+tha+doggfather&hl=en&ei=bTf1TZKNFpGosAOHr7W2Cw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CE4Q6AEwCDgK#v=onepage&q=snoop%20dogg%20tha%20doggfather&f=false& |title=Trouble Funk |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |page=50 |date=February 1997 |issn=0886-3032}}</ref>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' praised the album stating that \"Even without Dr. Dre behind the board, Snoop and his studio team concoct an intoxicating blend of old-school funk and gangsta cool\", but also noted that \"There's not much to love in the album's attitude toward sex, drugs, and first-degree murder.\" [[Muzik]] said, \"...a more angular, spiky, old school-influenced vehicle for the Dogg Father to strut his matter-of-act rhymes over... you [are taken in] by the strength of the rhyming...\". [[Melody Maker]] ranked it #49 on Melody Maker's list of 1996's 'Albums Of The Year'. The [[Los Angeles Times]] reported that \"Snoop still is one of rap's most electrifying performers. But unlike \"[[Doggystyle]]\" and the \"[[Murder Was the Case]]\" soundtrack, few of the beats on this album rival his rapping prowess.\" They complimented some of the tracks, calling 'Doggfather' \"... the epitome of cool smoothness. Over a slow-rolling Daz and DJ Pooh track\" 'Freestyle Conversation' \"...an Outkast-style exercise in which Snoop speaks a mile a minute, but still manages to maintain a funky rhythm\", 'Gold Rush' a \"funky pistolero track\" and the [[Biz Markie]] remake '[[Vapors (song)|Vapors]]' \"the album's real gem\". The review went on to conclude that \"Tha Doggfather may not be Doggystyle, but Snoop shows that he has the prowess and the talent to survive.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-11-10/entertainment/ca-63105_1_tha-doggfather& | work=Los Angeles Times | title=Snoop Still Has Some Bite | date=November 10, 1996}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]'' predicted that the album would chart in the top ten due to his presence in the music industry. They also stated that \"The album has a few obligatory mentions of sexual exploits and gun-toting, usually delegated to guest rappers. But most of the raps are about his position as a hit-maker. He still has one of the most distinctive deliveries in rap: a casual, nasal, conversational tone that sounds leisurely even when he's barreling forward. His producers are a little less slick than Dr. Dre was, but they have supplied swampy bass riffs and catchy backup choruses, drawing heavily (like Dr. Dre) on George Clinton's P-Funk. Snoop Doggy Dogg insists, and ''Tha Doggfather'' does that, maintaining a party atmosphere. Yet while it insists that gangsta rap isn't dead, it plays down tough-guy tales in favor of a star's pronouncements.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/11/26/arts/machismo-in-rap-atop-the-charts.html | work=The New York Times | first=Jon | last=Pareles | title=Machismo In Rap Atop The Charts | date=November 26, 1996}}</ref> [[AllMusic]] reviewer Stephen Thomas Erlewine noted that the album runs on too long at over 70 minutes and \"Though it works the same G-funk territory, the bass is less elastic and there is considerably less sonic detail\". But also praised the album by stating \"Though the music isn't original, and the lyrics break no new territory, the execution is strong -- Snoop's rapping and rhyming continue to improve, while the bass-heavy funk is often intoxicating.\" He ended the review stating \"...the album is a fine follow-up to one of the most successful hip-hop albums in history.\"<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/>\n\n===Commercial reception===\nBefore the release of the album many were questioning if the album would become lost in the turmoil and tragedy of the label, or even to be bypassed in the rush of Tupac's [[The Don Killuminati: The 7 Day Theory|posthumous album]]. However retailers thought differently such as Violet Brown, urban music buyer for the Wherehouse music chain. \"Customer anticipation has been huge. As soon as record executives found out they were opening against Snoop [this week], they shifted the release dates of some rival rap albums to avoid the Snoop sales rush.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-11-11/entertainment/ca-63540_1_executive-vice-president& | work=Los Angeles Times | title=Ready, Set . . . All Hail to the Sony Chief | date=November 11, 1996}}</ref> The album debuted at number one with strong first week sales of 479,000 copies, with Tupac at number two with second week sales of 250,000 (proving that Death Row still had a strong hold on the pop charts). While falling short of Doggystyle's 803,000 in the first week sold (the record at the time for a rap album), the album still was the third-highest rap debut of that year behind Shakur's \"[[All Eyez on Me]]\" (566,000 first-week copies) and \"Killuminati\" (664,000 copies), and it ranks fourth overall on the year's list of top debuts, which is headed by [[Metallica]]'s \"Load\" (680,000 copies).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-11-21/entertainment/ca-1151_1_tupac-shakur& | work=Los Angeles Times | first=Shauna | last=Snow | title=Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and international news services and the nation's press | date=November 21, 1996}}</ref> The album has sold over two million copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2SUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA104&dq=death+row+soundscan&hl=en&ei=VZ9NTqu8KefkiAKP1pVw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=death%20row%20soundscan&f=false& |title=Knight Moves |date=October 2001 |magazine=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |page=104 |location=New York |publisher=InterMedia Partners |issn=1070-4701 |accessdate={{date|2011-10-01|mdy}}}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{tracklist\n| total_length = \n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| title1  = Intro\n| note1 = \n| writer1 = \n| extra1 = \n| length1 = 0:46\n\n| title2  = [[Doggfather]]\n| note2 = featuring [[Charlie Wilson (musician)|Charlie Wilson]]\n| writer2 = [[Snoop Dogg|Calvin Broadus, Jr.]], [[Daz Dillinger|Delmar Arnaud]]\n| extra2 = [[Daz Dillinger|Dat Nigga Daz]]\n| length2 = 3:57\n\n| title3 = Ride 4 Me\n| note3 = \n| writer3 = Broadus, Jr., Ralph Aiken, Tyrone Crum, Keith Harrison, Robert Neal, Jr., Roger Parker, Clarence Satchell\n| extra3 = \n| length3 = 1:01\n\n| title4 = Up Jump tha Boogie\n| note4 = featuring [[Charlie Wilson (musician)|Charlie Wilson]] and [[Kurupt|Kurupt tha Kingpin]] \n| writer4 = Broadus, Jr., [[Kurupt|Ricardo Brown]], [[DJ Pooh|Mark Jordan]]\n| extra4 = [[DJ Pooh]]\n| length4 = 4:43\n\n| title5  = Freestyle Conversation\n| note5 = \n| writer5 = Broadus, Jr., [[Soopafly|